    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Start by using a static memory profiler like Valgrind (if the hardware supports it) or a tool from the Clang ecosystem such as AddressSanitizer to pinpoint the exact module and line number where memory is being allocated but never freed. Since you're dealing with an embedded automotive system, also consider the Resource Usage Monitor (RUM) from the AUTOSAR architecture, which can track memory consumption over time to identify subtle leaks in the standard library or third-party drivers. Once you've identified the suspect area, review the code for dynamic allocations like `new` or `malloc` and ensure every corresponding `delete` or `free` is accounted for, paying special attention to exception-safe constructs or loops that might skip cleanup logic. If the leak persists despite these checks, check for instance leaks in class constructors or destruction order issues, as C++ objects in embedded systems can sometimes outlive their expected lifetimes if not explicitly managed by the control unit's scheduler.",
      "source": "target",
